title: Steering Committee on Strategic Review on Healthcare Manpower Planning and Professional Development established (with photo)
content_text:
p>
    The Government today (January 31) announced the setting up of a steering 
    committee to conduct a strategic review on healthcare manpower planning and 
    professional development. The Steering Committee held its first meeting 
    today.  The Steering Committee is chaired by the Secretary for Food and Health, Dr 
    York Chow, and comprises 19 non-official members and five ex-officio 
    members. The appointments will take immediate effect and end upon the 
    completion of the review. The Steering Committee is tasked to conduct a strategic review of healthcare

completion of the review. The Steering Committee is tasked to conduct a strategic review of healthcare 
    manpower planning and professional development in Hong Kong. It will put 
    forward recommendations on how to cope with anticipated demand for 
    healthcare manpower, strengthen professional training and facilitate 
    professional development having regard to the findings of the strategic 
    review, with a view to ensuring the healthy and sustainable development of 
    Hong Kong's healthcare system.  Dr Chow said, "As announced in the Chief Executive's 2011 Policy Address,

the strategic review is part of a three-pronged action plan to take forward 
    healthcare reform initiatives based on the outcome of the Second Stage 
    Public Consultation on Healthcare Reform.  "The strategic review underlines the Government's commitment to ensuring an 
    adequate supply of healthcare manpower professionals as the healthcare 
    system grows and expands to cater for the community's future healthcare 
    needs." Non-official members of the Steering Committee comprise personalities from a 
    wide range of backgrounds and interests, including the healthcare,

wide range of backgrounds and interests, including the healthcare, 
    education, social services and business sectors, as well as overseas 
    experts. Ex-officio members include representatives from the Labour and 
    Welfare Bureau, the Education Bureau and the Department of Health.  "With their wealth of experience in public service and the healthcare field, 
    I believe that members of the Steering Committee will contribute to the 
    formulation of pertinent and balanced recommendations in the overall public 
    interest. "I would like to thank all members for accepting the challenge of this

interest. "I would like to thank all members for accepting the challenge of this 
    important mission. I look forward to working with them for the betterment of 
    our healthcare system," Dr Chow added. In carrying out its work, the Steering Committee will be underpinned by a 
    Co-ordinating Committee, to be chaired by the Permanent Secretary for Food 
    and Health (Health), and six consultative sub-groups to be formed thereunder
